VMany NAT firewalls or VPN server time out idle sessions after a certain period of time to keep their trunks clean. Sometimes the interval between session drops is 24 hours, but on many commodity firewalls, connections are killed after as little as 300 seconds, and this can be a problem if you are working on <a class="excerpt-more" href="http://linuxaria.com/howto/how-to-keep-ssh-connections-alive-on-linux?lang=en">[...]</a><div class="yarpp-related-rss">\u000a\u000aRelated posts:<ol>\u000a<li><a href="http://linuxaria.com/howto/permanent-ssh-tunnels-with-autossh?lang=en" rel="bookmark" title="Permanent SSH Tunnels with autossh">Permanent SSH Tunnels with autossh</a></li>\u000a<li><a href="http://linuxaria.com/howto/knockd-to-secure-your-ports-on-linux?lang=en" rel="bookmark" title="Knockd, to secure your ports on Linux">Knockd, to secure your ports on Linux</a></li>\u000a</ol>\u000a<img src="http://yarpp.org/pixels/ba2be3fba9b21a2a23229e17892b86c0" />\u000a</div>
